00:37:57,478 --> 00:37:59,309
Katie can fly back,
bring the dogs out.

494
00:37:59,398 --> 00:38:01,992
I'll wait here and...
I'll fly out with the dogs later.

495
00:38:02,078 --> 00:38:05,514
No, that's out of the question.
That could be stage three frostbite

496
00:38:05,598 --> 00:38:08,351
and heaven knows what nerve damage
has already been done.

497
00:38:08,438 --> 00:38:11,987
Jerry, he's right.
I'll come right back. I promise.

498
00:38:12,078 --> 00:38:14,353
Let's get ready to pull out of here.

499
00:38:17,038 --> 00:38:18,596
Take them out.

500
00:38:18,678 --> 00:38:20,714
Watch his head.
Jer. I need some help.

501
00:38:20,798 --> 00:38:22,436
Be careful with that leg.

502
00:38:27,278 --> 00:38:29,746
Knock down the stretcher,
Rosemary.

503
00:38:31,078 --> 00:38:33,433
Coop, come help me
tighten the dogs' collars

504
00:38:33,518 --> 00:38:35,952
so they don't get loose.
Come on. Max! Come on!

505
00:38:36,038 --> 00:38:37,756
Good boy, Max.

506
00:38:42,678 --> 00:38:45,033
Come on, buddy. Come here.

507
00:38:47,478 --> 00:38:49,992
Come here, Max. Come here, Max.

508
00:38:50,078 --> 00:38:52,638
- Come here.
- Good boy. Good boy, Max.

509
00:38:52,718 --> 00:38:55,312
- All right. Here we go.
- We won't be long.

510
00:38:55,398 --> 00:38:57,354
Easy, Max. Easy.

511
00:38:57,438 --> 00:39:00,111
- Let's get the other ones.
- All right.

512
00:39:01,798 --> 00:39:03,709
Hang in there, big guy.

513
00:39:10,358 --> 00:39:12,394
That's the last of 'em.

514
00:39:13,238 --> 00:39:14,830
All right, Maya.

515
00:39:14,918 --> 00:39:18,069
You keep 'em in line, all right,
and I'll be back. I promise.

516
00:39:18,158 --> 00:39:20,547
Be good. That's my girl!

517
00:39:49,798 --> 00:39:52,471
All right, buckle tight.
This one's gonna be rough.

518
00:39:54,958 --> 00:39:58,712
- Coop, I know you got that fear...
- Major... major fear of flying? Yeah.

519
00:42:26,078 --> 00:42:27,067
Hey.

520
00:42:27,598 --> 00:42:28,872
Hey!

521
00:42:29,198 --> 00:42:31,075
Finally.

522
00:42:31,918 --> 00:42:33,192
Oh, man.

523
00:42:33,278 --> 00:42:35,838
Oh, you...
you are so lucky you passed out.

524
00:42:35,918 --> 00:42:36,907
We...

525
00:42:36,998 --> 00:42:38,875
We were bouncing around up there, man,

526
00:42:38,958 --> 00:42:41,518
like one of those beach balls
at Dodger Stadium.

527
00:42:41,598 --> 00:42:44,635
And Katie was yelling at me
the whole time to stop screaming,

528
00:42:44,718 --> 00:42:47,391
but I couldn't do it.
It was way too intense, man.

529
00:42:47,478 --> 00:42:49,230
It was crazy.

530
00:42:50,038 --> 00:42:51,630
Where is everybody?

531
00:42:51,718 --> 00:42:54,027
Right here.
Everyone's here at Mactown.

532
00:42:54,118 --> 00:42:56,393
Davis is good. You're good.

533
00:42:56,478 --> 00:42:59,151
You still have your hands,
which is good.

534
00:42:59,238 --> 00:43:01,672
Everything's...
everything's all good, man.

535
00:43:02,118 --> 00:43:04,074
Did Katie get the dogs OK?

536
00:43:04,998 --> 00:43:06,795
Yeah, well...

537
00:43:11,958 --> 00:43:13,232
No.

538
00:43:13,318 --> 00:43:16,071
They were telling her
that-that she should wait, maybe,

539
00:43:16,158 --> 00:43:18,308
you know, until things got better.

540
00:43:18,678 --> 00:43:22,227
Jer? It's been snowing
since we got here, man.

541
00:43:25,278 --> 00:43:26,791
Dude...

542
00:43:33,118 --> 00:43:35,712
Hey. You're finally up.

543
00:43:37,158 --> 00:43:39,433
- How are your hands feeling?
- They're fine.

544
00:43:39,518 --> 00:43:42,555
- How soon can we go back?
- I think you should get some rest, OK?

545
00:43:42,638 --> 00:43:43,627
No, Katie. How soon?

546
00:43:43,718 --> 00:43:46,027
The weather's gotten worse.
No one's flying in.

547
00:43:46,118 --> 00:43:47,676
When is it gonna get better?

548
00:43:48,718 --> 00:43:52,154
They've cancelled the winter teams.
No one's going in till spring.

549
00:44:02,078 --> 00:44:03,955
I need it now!

550
00:44:04,758 --> 00:44:05,952
Excuse me, commander?

551
00:44:06,038 --> 00:44:08,313
- Who are you?
- Jerry Shepard. I'm with NSF.

552
00:44:08,398 --> 00:44:10,195
- Andy Harrison's crew?
- Yeah.

553
00:44:10,278 --> 00:44:13,429
We need a plane to the field base.
We weren't entirely evacuated.

554
00:44:13,518 --> 00:44:16,078
What? I ordered everybody
out of there yesterday.

555
00:44:16,158 --> 00:44:18,718
No, not everybody.
We left eight dogs there, sir.

556
00:44:18,798 --> 00:44:19,947
Dogs?

557
00:44:20,038 --> 00:44:23,792
I've got over 200 people, ten winter
teams to evacuate to New Zealand.

558
00:44:23,878 --> 00:44:26,312
Right. These dogs
are a part of our team, NSF.

559
00:44:26,398 --> 00:44:29,708
Captain, we've got a big problem
with some of the engines icing up.

560
00:44:29,798 --> 00:44:34,394
- We have to start moving some planes.
- Son, look. This is today.

561
00:44:34,478 --> 00:44:37,117
We've got a two-day window,
then another storm hits.

562
00:44:37,198 --> 00:44:39,348
If it lasts till here,
which they say it will,

563
00:44:39,438 --> 00:44:41,747
then we're into winter
and nobody flies.

564
00:44:41,838 --> 00:44:44,636
We don't have enough supplies
to keep everybody here.

565
00:44:44,718 --> 00:44:48,074
- So I'm a little busy right now.
- All we need is a plane, sir...

566
00:44:48,158 --> 00:44:50,388
- Do you want us to do that, sir?
- Do what?

567
00:44:50,478 --> 00:44:53,436
- Start moving some planes.
- Will you give me one minute?

568
00:44:55,078 --> 00:44:58,229
Listen. If we could just get a plane
like the one that we flew in on,

569
00:44:58,318 --> 00:45:00,149
it would only take three hours.

570
00:45:00,518 --> 00:45:03,510
Son, the only thing
we've got left are C-130s

571
00:45:03,598 --> 00:45:05,907
and they sure as hell
can't land at a field base.

572
00:45:07,398 --> 00:45:09,707
We can't just leave 'em out there.

573
00:45:10,958 --> 00:45:13,631
There's nothing I can do. I'm sorry.

574
00:45:15,198 --> 00:45:18,986
- Let's start moving those planes.
- Yes, sir, right away, captain.

575
00:45:28,678 --> 00:45:29,997
Yeah, come in.

576
00:45:31,118 --> 00:45:32,517
Hey.

577
00:45:33,238 --> 00:45:35,354
How we doing?

578
00:45:35,438 --> 00:45:38,396
When's your flight leave?
You and Rosie?

579
00:45:38,478 --> 00:45:41,311
A couple hours ahead of you,
Coop and the doc.

580
00:45:43,478 --> 00:45:45,594
Jerry, I'm so sorry.

581
00:45:46,278 --> 00:45:48,269
I'm really sorry, Jerry.

582
00:45:48,358 --> 00:45:51,509
I don't want to talk about it.
You want a drink?

583
00:45:51,718 --> 00:45:52,833
Sure.

584
00:45:55,998 --> 00:46:00,753
- Fresca.
- Yeah, sorry. That's all I got.

585
00:46:00,838 --> 00:46:04,717
You know this wasn't your fault.
This wasn't anybody's fault.

586
00:46:04,798 --> 00:46:07,596
- We just left 'em.
- Come on. We didn't just leave them.

587
00:46:07,678 --> 00:46:10,590
Don't do this to yourself.
The dogs are strong.

588
00:46:10,678 --> 00:46:12,031
Maybe there's a chance.

589
00:46:12,118 --> 00:46:15,235
We tightened their collars
so they wouldn't get loose.

590
00:46:18,118 --> 00:46:20,029
Listen, I...

591
00:46:20,118 --> 00:46:21,676
I know...

592
00:46:21,758 --> 00:46:25,273
I know you want me to find
a way to get us back there somehow.

593
00:46:25,358 --> 00:46:27,189
I know you're disappointed in me.

594
00:46:29,398 --> 00:46:30,956
No.

595
00:46:34,998 --> 00:46:38,115
You know, sometimes you just
have to lower your expectations.

596
00:46:48,198 --> 00:46:50,951
You know what, Jerry?
I'm sorry. I really am.

597
00:46:53,118 --> 00:46:54,790
I've got to go pack.

598
00:48:00,958 --> 00:48:04,997
Fill this out. Take it down to admin.
Just follow the red line on the floor.

599
00:48:05,078 --> 00:48:07,546
With any luck,
you could have funding by August.

600
00:48:07,638 --> 00:48:09,515
August?

601
00:48:09,598 --> 00:48:13,034
No, wait. I don't think you understand.
In a few days those dogs...

602
00:48:13,118 --> 00:48:14,346
I have to go now.

603
00:48:14,438 --> 00:48:17,111
I'm sorry, Mr Shepard.
Once winter sets in,

604
00:48:17,198 --> 00:48:20,270
as you know, there's no
coming or goings down there.

605
00:48:20,358 --> 00:48:22,667
We had to cancel
the winter teams this year.

606
00:48:22,758 --> 00:48:26,990
- Couldn't get 'em in before the storm.
- There must be somebody going south.

607
00:48:27,078 --> 00:48:31,947
Mr Shepard, be reasonable. This is
the biggest Antarctic storm in 25 years.

608
00:48:32,038 --> 00:48:35,235
If you don't believe me,
take a look at this weather report.

609
00:50:13,718 --> 00:50:16,232
Yeah, good, good.

610
00:50:16,318 --> 00:50:18,912
- Where's the rocket going?
- What a surprise!

611
00:50:18,998 --> 00:50:20,716
- To Mars, Dad.
- Come on in.

612
00:50:20,798 --> 00:50:22,197
Yeah?

613
00:50:22,278 --> 00:50:23,870
Well, look who I found.

614
00:50:24,518 --> 00:50:26,873
Hey. Hey, world traveller.

615
00:50:26,958 --> 00:50:28,710
- How you been?
- I'm good, I'm good.

616
00:50:28,798 --> 00:50:31,107
- How's your fingers?
- Oh, I get to keep 'em.

617
00:50:31,198 --> 00:50:32,392
- Great.
- How's the leg?

618
00:50:32,478 --> 00:50:35,231
Hard to tell.
The cast is great, thanks to Eric.

619
00:50:35,318 --> 00:50:37,434
There's a pot of coffee
in the kitchen, so...

620
00:50:37,518 --> 00:50:39,588
Eric, let's go find
a real colouring book.

621
00:50:39,678 --> 00:50:41,669
- What a great surprise.
- Give you a hand?

622
00:50:41,758 --> 00:50:43,191
- I'm all right.
- You got it?

623
00:50:43,278 --> 00:50:46,350
So, what brings you to LA?

624
00:50:47,518 --> 00:50:49,474
I brought you something.

625
00:50:56,958 --> 00:50:59,074
Thanks.

626
00:50:59,158 --> 00:51:02,150
I gotta get back there. Right now.

627
00:51:02,758 --> 00:51:06,990
I can't sleep at night. I've been
to NSF, agencies, foundations.

628
00:51:07,078 --> 00:51:10,354
I've been to TV networks to convince
them to follow me with a camera.

629
00:51:10,438 --> 00:51:13,510
Anything to raise money.
It just... It all takes too long.

630
00:51:13,598 --> 00:51:17,034
Now I've only got one week to get
back down there before winter hits.

631
00:51:17,118 --> 00:51:21,396
Then no one gets in for six months.
You've got those guys in your pocket.

632
00:51:21,478 --> 00:51:23,912
The... the science fund guys.

633
00:51:23,998 --> 00:51:27,627
- The university endowment?
- They'd do anything for you right now.

634
00:51:28,438 --> 00:51:31,475
- Jerry, listen to what you're saying.
- No, it would just be me,

635
00:51:31,558 --> 00:51:33,753
just a three-day trip in.
You could tell 'em.

636
00:51:33,838 --> 00:51:37,547
- Tell 'em I'm scouting your next trip.
- They'd be throwing their money away.

637
00:51:37,638 --> 00:51:40,436
- No, they wouldn't.
- Even if you could get down there,

638
00:51:40,518 --> 00:51:41,917
- by now it's 50 below.
- No.

639
00:51:41,998 --> 00:51:44,990
Jerry, be realistic.
It's already been...

640
00:51:45,078 --> 00:51:47,797
I know how long it's been.

641
00:51:47,878 --> 00:51:50,836
But I need to know for sure.
I have to go.

642
00:51:51,438 --> 00:51:54,316
It's not possible, Jerry.

643
00:51:55,278 --> 00:51:57,792
It's just not possible.

644
00:51:59,478 --> 00:52:01,787
You gotta find a way
to forget about all this.

645
00:52:03,798 --> 00:52:05,231
Forget?

646
00:52:06,838 --> 00:52:08,715
And you can do that?

647
00:58:21,718 --> 00:58:24,027
<i>Hey, Jer. It's Kate.</i>

648
00:58:24,118 --> 00:58:26,473
<i>It's been a week.</i>
<i>Just checking if you're home.</i>

649
00:58:26,558 --> 00:58:27,752
<i>Bye.</i>

650
00:58:31,598 --> 00:58:34,988
<i>Jer, it's Kate again.</i>
<i>Call me back. Bye.</i>

651
01:04:18,478 --> 01:04:19,547
Over here.

652
01:04:21,158 --> 01:04:23,388
Remember, the ocean
has a mind of its own.

653
01:04:24,078 --> 01:04:26,387
So respect the ocean. Stay alert.

654
01:04:27,838 --> 01:04:30,796
Now, go on ahead and take the paddle
like this, in both hands.

655
01:04:33,118 --> 01:04:34,153
There you go.

656
01:04:34,238 --> 01:04:37,867
We're gonna do an even paddle,
alternating blades.

657
01:04:40,438 --> 01:04:41,712
Like that.

658
01:04:43,558 --> 01:04:45,594
Hey, Al, will you take over for me?

659
01:04:50,678 --> 01:04:52,669
Hey, what are you doing here?

660
01:04:52,758 --> 01:04:56,148
Somebody told me Jerry Shepard
was working at the kiddie pool.

661
01:04:56,238 --> 01:04:59,469
I said, "No way.
I have to see that for myself."

662
01:04:59,558 --> 01:05:01,833
Is that why you're here?
You're here to mock me?

663
01:05:01,918 --> 01:05:05,115
I'm the chauffeur.
Somebody else wanted to see you.

664
01:05:05,198 --> 01:05:08,907
Brandy! Come here. Go see Jerry!

665
01:05:10,758 --> 01:05:11,827
Wow.

666
01:05:11,918 --> 01:05:15,547
- Look who's all grown up and beautiful.
- She's smart too. Like you said.

667
01:05:15,638 --> 01:05:18,994
Is she? Let's see
how well she's got you trained, then.

668
01:05:21,158 --> 01:05:23,035
Go get it!

669
01:05:27,038 --> 01:05:29,472
She's looking good.

670
01:05:29,558 --> 01:05:32,197
But I'm still not sure
what you're doing here.

671
01:05:32,278 --> 01:05:35,315
Come on. You didn't return my calls.
I got worried.

672
01:05:35,398 --> 01:05:39,471
- I've been busy.
- Oh, yeah, I can see that.

673
01:05:39,558 --> 01:05:42,152
What about you?
What have you been up to?

674
01:05:42,238 --> 01:05:45,275
Nothing much. I'm seeing somebody.

675
01:05:47,198 --> 01:05:48,836
- Really.
- Yeah, I mean,

676
01:05:48,918 --> 01:05:52,274
I'm not seeing him for long,
but I kind of like him.

677
01:05:52,358 --> 01:05:56,431
He's such the opposite of us.
A complete head guy.

678
01:05:56,518 --> 01:05:58,827
He's an engineer.

679
01:05:59,438 --> 01:06:01,235
Like on a train?

680
01:06:01,638 --> 01:06:03,276
Shut up.

681
01:06:07,478 --> 01:06:08,593
- Yeah.
- Good girl.

682
01:06:11,398 --> 01:06:12,831
Go, Brandy!

683
01:06:19,198 --> 01:06:22,873
So I heard you pulled yourself
off the McKinley expedition.

684
01:06:24,198 --> 01:06:26,996
Listen, I know leaving the dogs
was hard for you.

685
01:06:27,078 --> 01:06:30,229
Well, it is what it is.
There's really nothing to talk about.

686
01:06:30,318 --> 01:06:32,309
Nothing to talk about? Jerry, come on.

687
01:06:32,398 --> 01:06:34,070
I don't want to talk about it.

688
01:06:34,718 --> 01:06:36,709
You can't keep
hiding out here, Jerry.

689
01:06:36,798 --> 01:06:40,029
I mean, come on.
Renting kayaks to nine-year-olds?

690
01:06:41,478 --> 01:06:43,946
Well, what am I supposed to do then?

691
01:06:44,038 --> 01:06:47,235
Maybe you can help me out or something
cos I'm not sure anymore.

692
01:06:47,318 --> 01:06:51,789
You know what you're supposed to do?
Let yourself off the hook.

693
01:06:51,878 --> 01:06:54,915
It doesn't mean that you have to forget.

694
01:07:46,238 --> 01:07:48,468
He knows a dog person
when he smells one.

695
01:07:48,558 --> 01:07:50,071
Hey, Mindo.

696
01:07:50,158 --> 01:07:52,626
- How you doing? Easy trip?
- Yeah, it wasn't bad.

697
01:07:52,718 --> 01:07:55,027
- Appreciate you seeing me.
- My pleasure.

698
01:07:55,118 --> 01:07:56,915
You're part of the family.

699
01:07:57,758 --> 01:08:00,397
Here. I thought you'd like to have this.

700
01:08:01,158 --> 01:08:03,467
Thanks. Come on in.

701
01:08:15,318 --> 01:08:17,673
So, you came to apologize?

702
01:08:19,558 --> 01:08:21,150
I just knew...

703
01:08:21,878 --> 01:08:24,438
I just knew that you raised 'em.

704
01:08:24,518 --> 01:08:29,148
You don't have to apologize to me.
It's not about being sorry for anything.

705
01:08:31,398 --> 01:08:32,626
What is it then?

706
01:08:36,838 --> 01:08:39,591
Back when I was a young man,

707
01:08:39,678 --> 01:08:43,796
my father ran a team of sled dogs
up in the Yukon.

708
01:08:44,638 --> 01:08:48,267
One summer he was out in the bush
walking with six of them.

709
01:08:48,998 --> 01:08:53,708
They came across a grizzly bear.
Young, but big.

710
01:08:53,798 --> 01:08:57,347
The first thing he did was maul
my father within an inch of his life.

711
01:08:57,438 --> 01:09:00,748
When he came to,
he saw that two of his dogs

712
01:09:00,838 --> 01:09:04,228
had been killed trying to save him.
The rest were gone.

713
01:09:05,318 --> 01:09:09,675
When he regained his strength,
he went out looking for his dogs.

714
01:09:09,758 --> 01:09:11,589
He said he had to.

715
01:09:14,358 --> 01:09:16,918
You know why I told you this story?

716
01:09:19,518 --> 01:09:21,748
Because I won't find my dogs.

717
01:09:22,438 --> 01:09:25,669
The story's not about the dogs.
It's about my father

718
01:09:25,758 --> 01:09:27,953
honouring what the dogs
had done for him.

719
01:09:29,518 --> 01:09:31,634
Jerry, what's important

720
01:09:31,718 --> 01:09:35,711
is finding that one thing
that will truly put your heart at rest.

721
01:12:17,878 --> 01:12:19,436
And now...

722
01:12:19,518 --> 01:12:21,952
And now, ladies and gentlemen,
please join with me

723
01:12:22,038 --> 01:12:26,190
in welcoming and honouring
the man who five months ago

724
01:12:26,278 --> 01:12:30,271
brought back from Antarctica
the first documented Mercury meteorite,

725
01:12:30,358 --> 01:12:31,950
Dr Davis McClaren.

726
01:12:39,798 --> 01:12:42,266
- Congratulations.
- Thank you.

727
01:12:43,518 --> 01:12:46,669
Thank you very much. There are
several people I wish to thank,

728
01:12:46,758 --> 01:12:49,113
but first and most important,
my family,

729
01:12:49,198 --> 01:12:52,110
my son, Eric,
and my wife, Dr Eve McClaren,

730
01:12:52,198 --> 01:12:56,237
for her patience as I travel
around the world on these expeditions,

731
01:12:56,318 --> 01:12:59,708
many of which could be better
described as wild-goose chases.

732
01:13:00,918 --> 01:13:03,990
I'd like to thank the university
for its continued support.

733
01:13:04,078 --> 01:13:06,228
I'd also like to take a moment

734
01:13:06,318 --> 01:13:10,755
to thank the entire team
at the NSF base,

735
01:13:10,838 --> 01:13:14,467
without whom this discovery

736
01:13:14,558 --> 01:13:18,676
and this scientist
would not have made it home.

737
01:13:28,758 --> 01:13:32,876
Thanks. Thanks.
Excuse me one second.

738
01:13:32,958 --> 01:13:34,516
- Thanks.
- Yeah, thanks. Hey.

739
01:13:34,598 --> 01:13:37,590
- There he is.
- Yeah. Scotch, rocks, please.

740
01:13:37,678 --> 01:13:39,953
The man of the hour. Congratulations.

741
01:13:40,038 --> 01:13:43,553
Well, I'm glad you could make it.
I wasn't sure you were gonna come down.

742
01:13:43,638 --> 01:13:45,230
Yeah.

743
01:13:45,318 --> 01:13:46,751
You know, about that...

744
01:13:46,838 --> 01:13:49,113
Last time I saw you,

745
01:13:49,198 --> 01:13:52,110
I tried to make my problems yours.
I shouldn't have done that.

746
01:13:52,198 --> 01:13:55,395
But it was hard to accept
that I couldn't get back to the dogs.

747
01:13:56,758 --> 01:13:58,555
So, where are you with all of that?

748
01:14:01,038 --> 01:14:03,552
I'm heading to New Zealand
later on tonight.

749
01:14:04,998 --> 01:14:07,307
So, you found a way back down?

750
01:14:07,398 --> 01:14:09,593
Part of the way.
I'll make it to Christchurch

751
01:14:09,678 --> 01:14:14,149
and if you hang out there long enough,
usually you can find a ride south.

752
01:14:14,238 --> 01:14:16,547
And if you don't?

753
01:14:18,558 --> 01:14:21,994
Well, it's like you said
to me the day that storm came in.

754
01:14:22,078 --> 01:14:24,956
You gotta take chances
for things you care about.

755
01:14:25,038 --> 01:14:26,710
Davis?

756
01:14:28,038 --> 01:14:30,996
Yeah, yeah. Just...
I'll be right with you.

757
01:14:31,078 --> 01:14:32,636
Go ahead, get back to the party.

758
01:14:32,718 --> 01:14:35,710
I wanna come in
and say congratulations once again.

759
01:14:35,798 --> 01:14:37,948
- Sure. Thanks for coming.
- You're welcome.

760
01:14:38,038 --> 01:14:40,996
- Give my best to your family.
- I will. And good luck, really.

761
01:14:41,078 --> 01:14:42,272
Thanks.

762
01:14:43,478 --> 01:14:45,469
Enjoy the evening.

763
01:14:58,078 --> 01:15:01,229
- Sitter says he's been down since 8.00.
- Oh, great.

764
01:15:01,318 --> 01:15:04,515
Which means he'll be up at 5.00.

765
01:15:09,198 --> 01:15:10,950
Hey, little man.

766
01:21:33,958 --> 01:21:36,028
- Hello.
- Hi.

767
01:21:36,118 --> 01:21:38,313
Is your boat for hire?

768
01:21:38,398 --> 01:21:41,037
- For what?
- I gotta get to McMurdo.

769
01:21:41,838 --> 01:21:43,829
Not a chance, mate.
It's a fishing boat.

770
01:21:43,918 --> 01:21:45,954
Looking for someone,
you know Bailies?

771
01:21:46,038 --> 01:21:48,472
- Yeah.
- It's just up there. It's a bar.

772
01:21:48,558 --> 01:21:52,631
- All right, thanks. No chance?
- Not in hell.

773
01:21:53,958 --> 01:21:56,677
You want me to take you
to Antarctica in the dead of winter

774
01:21:56,758 --> 01:21:58,191
on a 70-foot fishing trawler?

775
01:21:59,398 --> 01:22:01,787
And I can pay you.
Not a lot, but everything I have.

776
01:22:01,878 --> 01:22:05,553
I'm sorry, mate. Everybody is looking
for a cheap ride out to McMurdo.

777
01:22:05,638 --> 01:22:07,629
My boat's a margarita blender.

778
01:22:07,718 --> 01:22:09,948
First chunk of ice we hit,
we'll break in half.

779
01:22:10,038 --> 01:22:11,710
I've seen your boat.
We can make it.

780
01:22:11,798 --> 01:22:14,949
- I'm desperate. You're my last option.
- No one in their right mind

781
01:22:15,038 --> 01:22:17,154
will take you in anything
but an icebreaker.

782
01:22:17,238 --> 01:22:20,833
Excuse me, sir.
The lady at the bar bought you a drink.

783
01:22:30,078 --> 01:22:32,592
No way. Excuse me.

784
01:22:35,998 --> 01:22:37,317
What are you doing here?

785
01:22:37,398 --> 01:22:40,276
Some guy needed a cheap pilot
for an expedition

786
01:22:40,358 --> 01:22:42,349
and I'm always cheap in the off-season.

787
01:22:42,438 --> 01:22:43,837
- Yeah?
- Yeah.

788
01:22:44,518 --> 01:22:46,713
- Good to see you.
- It's good to see you too.

789
01:22:47,638 --> 01:22:51,028
- So, where are you going?
- Same place I'm going.

790
01:22:54,558 --> 01:22:55,957
What the hell?

791
01:22:56,038 --> 01:22:58,598
- What's up, Jer?
- What's going on, buddy?

792
01:22:58,678 --> 01:23:00,475
- Hey, buddy.
- How you been?

793
01:23:00,558 --> 01:23:02,071
- Nice to see you.
- I missed you.

794
01:23:02,158 --> 01:23:04,149
Same here.

795
01:23:04,238 --> 01:23:06,957
What's really going on?
What kind of expedition is this?

796
01:23:07,038 --> 01:23:09,916
That'd be an NSF expedition.

797
01:23:09,998 --> 01:23:12,068
Yeah, I had a trip that was cut short.

798
01:23:12,158 --> 01:23:15,548
It turns out I got a couple of weeks
of grant money left and...

799
01:23:15,638 --> 01:23:16,957
So here we are.

800
01:23:17,318 --> 01:23:19,195
You're the man. You are the man.

801
01:23:19,278 --> 01:23:21,348
How long you think
it'll take you to pack?

802
01:23:21,438 --> 01:23:25,477
- You know me, I'm always packed.
- Well, this way.

803
01:23:25,558 --> 01:23:28,026
Yeah! Yeah.

804
01:23:28,118 --> 01:23:29,346
Let's go! Let's go!

805
01:23:35,278 --> 01:23:36,631
Come on in, boys.

806
01:23:39,398 --> 01:23:41,275
This is crazy. I never expected this.

807
01:23:41,358 --> 01:23:43,588
Sometimes you gotta
raise your expectations.

808
01:23:49,438 --> 01:23:51,713
- Cooper, how you doing?
- I'd rather not talk.

809
01:23:51,798 --> 01:23:53,231
- OK.
- Thanks.

810
01:25:10,758 --> 01:25:14,637
Polarsyssel, this is helicopter
Lima-November-Oscar-Mike-Bravo

811
01:25:14,718 --> 01:25:16,470
requesting to land on your vessel.

812
01:25:16,558 --> 01:25:18,753
<i>Roger,</i>
<i>Lima-November-Oscar-Mike-Bravo.</i>

813
01:25:18,838 --> 01:25:21,193
- <i>You're clear to land.</i>
- Here we go, boys.

814
01:26:10,758 --> 01:26:13,192
- Hey.
- Hey.

815
01:26:16,078 --> 01:26:18,273
I thought you might like some company.

816
01:26:18,358 --> 01:26:20,235
Sure.

817
01:26:23,478 --> 01:26:26,151
It's a good night for stargazing.

818
01:26:31,598 --> 01:26:34,192
Shooting stars mean good luck, right?

819
01:26:36,078 --> 01:26:37,557
Jerry, you know,

820
01:26:37,638 --> 01:26:40,516
this may not be easy, what we find.

821
01:26:40,598 --> 01:26:42,748
I know that.

822
01:26:42,838 --> 01:26:45,830
But whatever we find,
the dogs deserve this trip.

823
01:26:49,078 --> 01:26:52,593
I'm glad you're here, Katie.
And I owe you one.

824
01:26:54,078 --> 01:26:57,991
You owe me for a lot of things.
This is not one of them.

825
01:26:58,078 --> 01:26:59,909
No, I'm serious.

826
01:26:59,998 --> 01:27:02,034
You always understood
why I had to do this.

827
01:27:05,638 --> 01:27:07,276
Careful, Jerry.

828
01:27:07,358 --> 01:27:09,474
You're starting to sound like a grownup.

829
01:27:11,478 --> 01:27:13,548
What about that
conductor friend of yours?

830
01:27:13,638 --> 01:27:16,436
- He's an engineer.
- Oh, yeah.

831
01:27:16,518 --> 01:27:18,986
We're not seeing each other any more.

832
01:27:22,678 --> 01:27:24,555
That's too bad.

833
01:29:31,518 --> 01:29:34,988
Shut her down, Mr Hansen.
Let's go take a look.

834
01:29:40,638 --> 01:29:42,754
What do you make of that?

835
01:29:42,838 --> 01:29:44,908
It's not good.

836
01:29:54,518 --> 01:29:57,112
The ice is six feet about here.

837
01:30:01,798 --> 01:30:03,948
The ice is deeper than we thought.

838
01:30:04,038 --> 01:30:07,508
I guess we shouldn't be surprised,
given the winter we just had.

839
01:30:07,598 --> 01:30:10,715
Come around the world and we
can't make it the last 100 miles.

840
01:30:11,918 --> 01:30:13,317
Sorry, mates.

841
01:30:13,398 --> 01:30:17,027
I guess now is last call
for a great idea.

842
01:30:18,278 --> 01:30:20,792
Simonetta.

843
01:30:20,878 --> 01:30:22,709
Simonetta who?

844
01:30:22,798 --> 01:30:25,915
His imaginary Italian girlfriend.
Come on, not now.

845
01:30:25,998 --> 01:30:28,671
An iceberg, all right,
broke off from an ice shelf.

846
01:30:28,758 --> 01:30:32,307
It blocked the route the Adlie
penguins take for their fishing waters.

847
01:30:32,398 --> 01:30:35,549
- I'm not seeing the relevance.
- Horses, doc. Rein 'em in.

848
01:30:35,638 --> 01:30:38,755
Now, I needed to map the new route
so researchers could find 'em.

849
01:30:38,838 --> 01:30:43,673
While I was following them, they
led me right past the Italian base...

850
01:30:43,758 --> 01:30:46,113
...where one Simonetta Pirelli

851
01:30:46,198 --> 01:30:48,666
whipped me up
a mean cup of hot chocolate.

852
01:30:48,758 --> 01:30:52,671
- Come on, what are you talking about?
- Step into my office.

853
01:30:54,678 --> 01:30:58,034
Our base is too far for the helicopter
to make it there, right?

854
01:30:58,118 --> 01:31:00,916
But the Italian base is,
like, half the distance.

855
01:31:00,998 --> 01:31:03,671
- The young man's right.
- Still leaves us short.

856
01:31:03,758 --> 01:31:04,827
Right. Hold on. See,

857
01:31:04,918 --> 01:31:07,386
all field bases
have the same basic stuff, right?

858
01:31:07,478 --> 01:31:11,027
But the Italian base is equipped
with the Lamborghini of snowcats.

859
01:31:11,118 --> 01:31:13,268
I'm telling you,
this thing is like a rocket.

860
01:31:13,358 --> 01:31:16,509
So we take one of these snowcats
to our base, do what we came to do,

861
01:31:16,598 --> 01:31:17,792
blow out of Dodge.

862
01:31:17,878 --> 01:31:20,676
And this way, I get to spend
a little less time flying.

863
01:31:20,758 --> 01:31:22,396
No offence, Katie.

864
01:31:29,758 --> 01:31:30,907
All right, let's go.

865
01:34:20,998 --> 01:34:22,954
There it is!

866
01:34:37,878 --> 01:34:40,790
The keys are in number two.
The shovels are around the side.

867
01:34:40,878 --> 01:34:42,550
We gotta dig this place out.

868
01:34:53,278 --> 01:34:54,916
It's hard.

869
01:35:17,438 --> 01:35:19,315
Sweet.

870
01:35:51,238 --> 01:35:53,035
All aboard!

871
01:35:53,118 --> 01:35:55,393
Nice snowcat, Coop.

872
01:36:07,678 --> 01:36:09,350
What?

873
01:36:14,238 --> 01:36:16,069
Not bad, huh, Jer?

874
01:36:16,158 --> 01:36:18,592
Well, what do you want me to say?
You're the man?

875
01:36:19,078 --> 01:36:20,511
That'd be nice.

876
01:36:21,758 --> 01:36:23,111
OK, you're the man.

877
01:36:24,038 --> 01:36:26,871
You are indeed the man, Cooper!
You are the man!

878
01:36:27,198 --> 01:36:28,950
<i>Grazie, Geraldo. Grazie.</i>

879
01:36:30,078 --> 01:36:32,717
And as for you, Crazy Katie,

880
01:36:32,798 --> 01:36:35,756
you know all those ridiculous flights
you put me through?

881
01:36:35,838 --> 01:36:37,351
Yeah.

882
01:36:37,438 --> 01:36:40,589
Payback is a dish best served cold.

883
01:36:40,678 --> 01:36:43,238
Cooper, I think that's "revenge".

884
01:39:56,398 --> 01:39:57,956
It's Old Jack.

885
01:40:01,918 --> 01:40:04,955
We came all this way and they
didn't even make it off the chain.

886
01:40:48,318 --> 01:40:50,468
They got off.

887
01:40:54,038 --> 01:40:55,232
They got loose!

888
01:41:45,158 --> 01:41:46,557
Max!

889
01:41:49,518 --> 01:41:51,395
Come on, kids!

890
01:41:51,478 --> 01:41:52,911
Come on!

891
01:42:00,158 --> 01:42:01,955
Come on, Max!

892
01:42:12,398 --> 01:42:13,797
Hey!

893
01:42:13,878 --> 01:42:15,834
Hey, Buck!

894
01:42:17,198 --> 01:42:18,711
Hey, Buck.

895
01:42:18,798 --> 01:42:20,390
Max, what you been doing?

896
01:42:20,478 --> 01:42:23,629
- OK, not the face! Not the face!
- No! You look so beautiful.

897
01:42:23,718 --> 01:42:26,710
OK, chill, boy! Chill, boy, not the...

898
01:42:26,798 --> 01:42:29,187
Good boy, Max. Good boy, Max.

899
01:42:34,198 --> 01:42:36,871
- Yeah...
- Told you we'd come back.

900
01:42:36,958 --> 01:42:38,949
Look at you guys.

901
01:42:39,038 --> 01:42:41,506
Shorty, come here.

902
01:42:41,598 --> 01:42:44,510
Not the... Hey, Jer!
A little help over here.

903
01:42:44,598 --> 01:42:46,236
A little help.

904
01:42:47,838 --> 01:42:50,193
Hey, Buck!
Leave him alone! Get over here!

905
01:42:53,438 --> 01:42:55,508
Thank you, Jer!

906
01:42:57,398 --> 01:42:58,592
Good boy, Buck.

907
01:42:59,678 --> 01:43:03,114
Shadow, Truman, Max and Shorty.

908
01:43:03,198 --> 01:43:05,428
Man, I don't believe it.

909
01:43:05,518 --> 01:43:07,474
Good boys.

910
01:43:07,558 --> 01:43:10,391
My five lucky stars.

911
01:43:12,998 --> 01:43:14,909
Almost perfect.

912
01:43:27,678 --> 01:43:29,714
Let's go home, kids. Come on.

913
01:43:33,318 --> 01:43:35,354
This should be enough to get us home.

914
01:43:35,438 --> 01:43:38,271
- Give me a hand with this.
- OK.

915
01:43:40,958 --> 01:43:42,596
All right, Shorty, up!

916
01:43:43,678 --> 01:43:46,067
Good boy! Come on, Shadow, let's go.

917
01:43:46,158 --> 01:43:48,626
Come on, buddy.
Come on, let's go. Get in the back.

918
01:43:48,718 --> 01:43:51,869
Come on! We're losing light here.
Party's over, come on.

919
01:43:51,958 --> 01:43:53,710
All right, Max, come on, buddy.

920
01:43:55,598 --> 01:43:57,714
- Wanna ride up front?
- Have it your way.

921
01:43:57,798 --> 01:44:00,073
Let's go. Up front. Ride with me.

922
01:44:00,158 --> 01:44:01,750
Come on, buddy. Jump up.

923
01:44:03,358 --> 01:44:05,110
Max! Max!

924
01:44:05,198 --> 01:44:07,029
Max!

925
01:44:21,478 --> 01:44:22,831
Maya.

926
01:44:48,318 --> 01:44:50,707
Maya.

927
01:44:50,798 --> 01:44:52,629
Come on now.

928
01:44:54,158 --> 01:44:56,069
Come on now.

929
01:44:58,558 --> 01:45:00,788
You did good.

930
01:45:00,878 --> 01:45:03,517
You did good, Max. Good boy.

931
01:45:03,598 --> 01:45:05,714
You brought her home.

932
01:45:07,598 --> 01:45:09,236
I'm sorry, girl.

933
01:45:28,758 --> 01:45:30,555
Maya?

934
01:45:32,078 --> 01:45:33,750
Hey.

935
01:45:35,438 --> 01:45:37,429
There's my girl.

936
01:45:38,918 --> 01:45:40,749
You're OK.

937
01:45:45,638 --> 01:45:47,549
How's my best girl doing?

938
01:45:48,198 --> 01:45:52,157
Good girl, Maya.
All right, let's get you home, OK?

939
01:45:52,238 --> 01:45:53,717
Let's get you home.

940
01:46:00,278 --> 01:46:02,428
Coop. Coop.

941
01:46:22,758 --> 01:46:25,477
- She gonna be OK?
- Yeah, she's gonna be fine.

942
01:46:27,438 --> 01:46:30,236
What do you say, Coop?
Let's fire her up and get out of here.

943
01:46:30,318 --> 01:46:32,912
Yes, sir. I'll just make room
for one more.

944
01:46:32,998 --> 01:46:34,113
All right.

945
01:46:34,198 --> 01:46:36,996
Give me a hand here, Katie.
Let's get her in.

946
01:46:41,438 --> 01:46:43,474
Come here, Maya.

947
01:46:43,558 --> 01:46:46,277
- Got her? There you go.
- I think so.

948
01:46:46,358 --> 01:46:47,996
All right, Max. Let's go, buddy.

949
01:46:48,758 --> 01:46:51,397
Come on. Good boy.

950
01:47:00,598 --> 01:47:01,633
How's your girl?

951
01:47:06,318 --> 01:47:07,671
She's good.

952
01:47:29,558 --> 01:47:32,789
All right. Here we go.

